Rating: 2
I used the thigh and legs attached to one another and cooked it for 5-7 minutes longer (in my toaster oven) and they were perfectly cooked. Very Juicy and crispy skin. Other than that there was not much flavor. I would like to try this again but increasing the herbs and allowing to marinate for a couple of hours or over-night. It might be a better idea to infuse the oil and let the flavors marry one another before applying to the chicken. This isn't a bad recipe. It just needs a bit of fixing to bring out the flavors.

Rating: 3
Easy guest recipe that looks attractive on a serving platter. I use thighs and triple (or more depending on the size of the thighs) the thyme and garlic. I add enough oil to coat all the chicken pieces, thyme and garlic. I let the chicken marinate in this mixture overnight in the refrigerator turning the pieces once or twice. I also make a mixture of chopped thyme and garlic paste and put a bit under the skin of each thigh before cooking. I've added the lemon slices partway through the cooking as called for in the recipe and put a piece under each thigh before cooking. I like the lemon under the thigh better; it creates nice lemony cooking juices to pass at the table. Some reviewers have disliked the high temperature/reduced cooking time. I find that it works very well -- especially if the chicken is not right out of the refrigerator.

